Such propositions Wyclif calls partitive, and he adds some remarks on so-called implicative pro- positions. Ablatives absolute can be turned into incidental propo- sitions.

The subject containing a term not in the nominative is next examined and expounded. The rule is that the genitive (or other case not the nominative) becomes universal in the second or negative exponent, V. g. ‘Every A of any Β is C Some A of some B is C, and no A of any* B is not C.³ This Wyclif proves by analysis of the proposition. There are, however, cases when this is not true: as ‘Every servant obedient to his master is liked by yon. Or ‘He is the master of an obedient servant.³ If the genitive precede the nomi- native, then the term that comes first is alone universal.
